<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
This species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. lentus" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="lentus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">H. lentus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Sharp, 1890, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. densus" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="densus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">H. densus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Sharp, 1890, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. sauteri" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="sauteri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">H. sauteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="d’Orchymont">d'Orchymont</normalizedToken>
, 1943 and 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. hainanensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="hainanensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">H. hainanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dong &amp; Bian, 2021 in size, form and other morphological characters, but it is very easy to distinguish from all known species by aedeagal features. Aedeagus (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 21–28" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 21 - 28. 21 - 23, 27 - 28 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov. 24 - 26 Helochares guoi Yang &amp; Jia, sp. nov. 21 protarsomeres 22 mesotarsomeres 23 metatarsomeres 24 - 28 aedeagus 24 ventral view 25 lateral view 26 dorsal view 27 dorsal view 28 lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.73458.figures21-28" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/624119" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">27-28</figureCitation>
) with median lobe slightly shorter than parameres, nearly rhombic, apex with a globular structure with a cluster of apical spines and with a long baseball-bat-shaped branch medially, membranous inner sac with some strong spinous protrusions. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jia &amp; Tang" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Helochares" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Helochares distinctus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="distinctus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Helochares distinctus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov. can easily be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. guoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="guoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">H. guoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Jia &amp; Yang, sp. nov. by its larger size, median lobe of the aedeagus with a globular structure with a cluster of spines apically and with a long baseball-bat-shaped branch medially; membranous inner sac with some less strongly spinous protrusions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Form and colour</emphasis>
(Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–4" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 4. Habitus 1 - 2 Helochares guoi Yang &amp; Jia, sp. nov. 1 dorsal view 2 ventral view 3 - 4 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov. 3 paratype, dorsal view 4 holotype, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.73458.figures1-4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/624116" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">3</figureCitation>
- 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 5–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 5 - 7. Habitus 5 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov.: ventral view 6 - 7 head, dorsal view 6 Helochares guoi Yang &amp; Jia, sp. nov. 7 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov .." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.73458.figures5-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/624117" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 5–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 5 - 7. Habitus 5 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov.: ventral view 6 - 7 head, dorsal view 6 Helochares guoi Yang &amp; Jia, sp. nov. 7 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov .." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.73458.figures5-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/624117" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">7</figureCitation>
). Body length 5 mm, body width 2.6 mm, oval, moderately convex. Dorsum of head, pronotum, elytra and clypeus yellow-brown, labrum dark brown. Antennae yellow-brown with club black. Maxillary palps uniformly yellow-brown. Labial palps yellow, not darkened apically. Venter, including legs, blackish brown, tarsomeres yellow-brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Head</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Antennae with scape ca as long as antennomeres 2 and 3 combined (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 20. 8 - 9 Helochares guoi Yang &amp; Jia, sp. nov. 8 antennae 9 maxillary palp 10 - 20 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov. 10 the antennae of fig 3 11 the antennae of fig 4 12 maxillary palp 13 mentum 14 apex of fifth abdominal ventrite 15 prosternum 16 mesoventrite 17 metaventrite 18 protarsomeres 19 mesotarsomeres 20 metatarsomeres." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.73458.figures8-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/624118" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">10-11</figureCitation>
). Maxillary palps ca 1.25 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as of width of head anterior to eyes; apical segment asymmetrical, slightly shorter than the penultimate in length (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 20. 8 - 9 Helochares guoi Yang &amp; Jia, sp. nov. 8 antennae 9 maxillary palp 10 - 20 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov. 10 the antennae of fig 3 11 the antennae of fig 4 12 maxillary palp 13 mentum 14 apex of fifth abdominal ventrite 15 prosternum 16 mesoventrite 17 metaventrite 18 protarsomeres 19 mesotarsomeres 20 metatarsomeres." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.73458.figures8-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/624118" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">12</figureCitation>
). Clypeo-labral margin straight medially. Labrum, frons and clypeus with systematic punctures (with setae) same size as ground punctures; frons and clypeus with ground punctation dense and coarse, distance between punctures 0.5-1.2
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
width of one puncture. Mentum subquadrate, with anterior margin strongly emarginate, slightly depressed medially, surface with some oblique wrinkles (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 20. 8 - 9 Helochares guoi Yang &amp; Jia, sp. nov. 8 antennae 9 maxillary palp 10 - 20 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov. 10 the antennae of fig 3 11 the antennae of fig 4 12 maxillary palp 13 mentum 14 apex of fifth abdominal ventrite 15 prosternum 16 mesoventrite 17 metaventrite 18 protarsomeres 19 mesotarsomeres 20 metatarsomeres." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.73458.figures8-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/624118" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">13</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Thorax</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Ground punctation on pronotum and elytron similar to that on head, distance between punctures 0.5-1.2
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
width of one puncture; anterior margin without very fine bead. Elytron with short scutellary series of punctures and 10 striae, punctures in striae distinctly coarser than ground punctures; systematic punctures as coarse as punctures in striae. Prosternum moderately elevated medially, not tectiform or carinate medially (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 20. 8 - 9 Helochares guoi Yang &amp; Jia, sp. nov. 8 antennae 9 maxillary palp 10 - 20 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov. 10 the antennae of fig 3 11 the antennae of fig 4 12 maxillary palp 13 mentum 14 apex of fifth abdominal ventrite 15 prosternum 16 mesoventrite 17 metaventrite 18 protarsomeres 19 mesotarsomeres 20 metatarsomeres." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.73458.figures8-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/624118" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">15</figureCitation>
), with a transverse groove anteriorly. Mesoventrite with a small posteromedial tubercle, not carinate medially (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 20. 8 - 9 Helochares guoi Yang &amp; Jia, sp. nov. 8 antennae 9 maxillary palp 10 - 20 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov. 10 the antennae of fig 3 11 the antennae of fig 4 12 maxillary palp 13 mentum 14 apex of fifth abdominal ventrite 15 prosternum 16 mesoventrite 17 metaventrite 18 protarsomeres 19 mesotarsomeres 20 metatarsomeres." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.73458.figures8-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/624118" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">16</figureCitation>
). Metaventrite without glabrous area posteromedially. Femora densely pubescent except at apex (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 20. 8 - 9 Helochares guoi Yang &amp; Jia, sp. nov. 8 antennae 9 maxillary palp 10 - 20 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov. 10 the antennae of fig 3 11 the antennae of fig 4 12 maxillary palp 13 mentum 14 apex of fifth abdominal ventrite 15 prosternum 16 mesoventrite 17 metaventrite 18 protarsomeres 19 mesotarsomeres 20 metatarsomeres." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.73458.figures8-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/624118" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">17</figureCitation>
). Meso-, and metasomeres 1 to 4 with dense long setae ventrally, posterior tarsomeres with a fringe of long swimming-hairs dorsally. Protarsal claws in male somewhat stronger and a little angularly curved, bearing a blunt basal tooth; mesotarsal claws as protarsals, but only moderately curved with a blunt tooth; metatarsal claws only moderately curved, with a blunt basal tooth (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 20. 8 - 9 Helochares guoi Yang &amp; Jia, sp. nov. 8 antennae 9 maxillary palp 10 - 20 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov. 10 the antennae of fig 3 11 the antennae of fig 4 12 maxillary palp 13 mentum 14 apex of fifth abdominal ventrite 15 prosternum 16 mesoventrite 17 metaventrite 18 protarsomeres 19 mesotarsomeres 20 metatarsomeres." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.73458.figures8-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/624118" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">18</figureCitation>
- 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 21–28" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 21 - 28. 21 - 23, 27 - 28 Helochares distinctus Jia &amp; Tang, sp. nov. 24 - 26 Helochares guoi Yang &amp; Jia, sp. nov. 21 protarsomeres 22 mesotarsomeres 23 metatarsomeres 24 - 28 aedeagus 24 ventral view 25 lateral view 26 dorsal view 27 dorsal view 28 lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.73458.figures21-28" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/624119" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">23</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.73458.figures8-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/624118" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" start="Figures 8–20" startId="F3">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
